## Known issues (fix these before experiments)
- finetune.py line 148: torch.cuda.amp.autocast → torch.amp.autocast('cuda', ...)
- PyG extensions (pyg-lib, torch-scatter, torch-sparse) have ABI mismatch
  → using pure-PyTorch fallbacks (correct but ~10-20% slower scatter ops)
  → non-blocking, do not spend time fixing unless performance is the bottleneck

## What we are building toward (publication)
- Target: NeurIPS/ICML 2026 Bio-ML Workshop
- Paper story: PPI message passing (0 → 1.85M edges) boosted AUROC 0.813 → 0.9626
- Still needed: 4-variant ablation table, zero-shot rare disease eval, paper sections

## Ablation variants to run (in order)
1. No-MP, No-Prompt: pure MLP baseline (disable GNN + FiLM)
2. No-MP + Prompt: GNN but no PPI edges + FiLM ON (use graph without gene-gene edges)
3. MP, No-Prompt: PPI edges ON, FiLM conditioning OFF (γ=1, β=0)
4. Full model: PPI edges ON + FiLM ON ← current best (AUROC 0.9626)
Run each with seed=42, 43, 44. Report mean ± std.

## Coding rules (always follow)
- Never rewrite entire files — output only changed functions with line numbers
- Never touch PROJECT_ROOT, path setup, or checkpoint save/load logic
- Keep num_workers configurable — never hardcode 0 as permanent fix
- Preserve fork-context patch in train.py (multiprocessing_context="fork")
- All fixes must include a comment explaining WHY, not just WHAT
- When editing notebook cells, reference the cell ID and output only that cell
- Do not add unrequested features; fix exactly what is asked

## Output discipline (saves tokens)
- No preamble. No "here is the code". Start with the code directly.
- No re-explaining logic that is already in comments
- When the fix is a single line, output just that line + its context (±3 lines)
- For multi-file changes, list affected files first, then show each patch
